text.tspan: 13.9 ANNEX 9 OFFICE FORMS FILING SYSTEMRev 1 - 30 Jun 2016Rev 0 - 14 Apr 20151INTRODUCTIONRev 1 - 01 Jul 2015This Manual is intended to serve as a guide for office personnel in carrying out their duties and responsibilities within the framework of applicable laws and companypolicy.Common sense is not to be dispensed with when interpreting the various principles laid down in the book, taking into account any special situation which may arise.Compliance and obedience to these instructions will do much to assist in maintaining high standards on board company vessels.Staff is expected not only to see that these regulations are carried out, but by themselves, set an example to their subordinates.2LEGAL AND OTHER REQUIREMENTSRev 2 - 01 Jul 2015The Company resolves to meet or exceed all relevant IMO, ILO, Flag State, Classification Society and local rules and regulations. Inaddition, ISO 9001, 14001 and OHSAS 18001 standards shall be met.The other regulatory requirements are obtained through feedback from customers, charterers, agents, local regulations, companyrequirements and other industry sources such as OCIMF, etc.HSEQA department shall maintain an updated list of legislations and standards applicable to ship management operations in a legalregister in order to evaluate compliance. The financial impact of such changes shall be brought to the attention of the owners insufficient detail and in ample time, to obtain their approval for any modifications and fitting of new equipment.All company vessels are provided with the latest editions of the necessary legal publications including Statutory Instruments.All company vessels shall comply with the requirements for presentation of certificates and other documents carried by the shippertaining to its registry, measurement, safety, manning, classification and other related matters for inspection by the appropriateauthorities. The Company receives advance notice of legislative development from numerous sources such as Classification Societies, P&I Clubs,Owners and trade journals. The HSEQA Superintendent shall track these developments and appropriate changes shall berecommended and implemented and where applicable shall keep the General Manager, and all other office departments and vesselsinformed by means of circulating the changes.It shall then be the responsibility of the Technical Superintendent to ensure compliance on board vessels. The legal requirementsapplicable to the company are posted in the company server for ease of reference. Further the legal compliance is checked by thesuperintendent during his visit, internal audits and audits by external agencies and by master and chief engineer while carrying outpost joining evaluation. The evaluation of compliance is further carried out by Environmental Management Representative (EMR) andrecord of the same is kept in legal register with legal and other requirements. The master shall request details of local environmental legislation from the agents on sending the initial ETA to the agents. TheHSEQA Superintendent shall advise all the vessels in the fleet of any local regulations, information of which is available to himthrough above-mentioned sources.A legal register shall be maintained for evaluating of compliance with legal and other requirements on a yearly basis. The latest copyof the legal register is appended below.Future regulatory requirements coming into force are covered in Company's Technical Circular T-2 and it is updated at least annuallybut more frequently if required.2.1PROCEDURES FOR ANTICIPATING & INCORPORATING CHANGES TO HSEQA REQUIREMENTS ANDVOLUNTARY UNDERTAKINGSRev 1 - 25 Jul 2014The HSEQA Superintendent shall keep abreast of the latest HSEQA requirements based on information available from varioussources such as the Flag States, Classification Societies and P&I Clubs and make recommendations to the General Managerregarding changes as well as improvements to the HSEQA System.The HSEQA Superintendent shall also anticipate changes to HSEQA requirements, including new requirements that may apply as aresult of changes in operations, and incorporate these changes into the HSEQA System.The Company shall anticipate and incorporate changes to Voluntary Undertakings based on Industry Best Practices, suggestions fromThird party audits, Quarterly and Annual Management Meetings and suggestions/ feedback from shore-side and ship side employees.The HSEQA Superintendent shall further evaluate all new or amended laws and regulations and their significant impact on theHSEQA activities of the Company. He shall inform appropriate personnel and disseminate such applicable laws and regulations to thevessels in the form of circular or amendments to the HSEQA Manuals which will describe how the requirements are to beimplemented and complied with.The changes will also be promulgated during training ashore and onboard and referenced in the Management Review report.2.2LEGAL REGISTERRev 1 - 25 Jul 2014DOCNO.ACTIVITYREGULATORY BODYREGULATIONDESCRIPTIONPICMETHODEVALUATIONOFCOMPLIANCEREMARKS(Yes/ No)1.aOperationalDischargesfrommachineryspaces.IMOMARPOLAnnex I -Regulationsfor thePrevention ofPollution byOil.Operationaldischarges frommachinery spacesallowed only through15 ppm OWS.C/O, C/E &MasterOil recordbook (Part I)YesLog bookrecordsmaintained onboard areverified duringship visits1.bDischarge inSpecialareasIMOMARPOLAnnex I –Special AreasSpecial Areas inwhich the dischargeof wastes from shipsis prohibited – InC/O, C/E &MasterOil recordbook (Part I)YesDuring ship visitonboard Logsare verified.
